GOLDEN TICKET
Attackers forge a TGT using the KRBTGT account hash.

🔍 What you look for
Kerberos logons with impossible lifetimes (10 years, etc.)
Logons for accounts that don’t exist
Kerberos tickets issued without a corresponding AS‑REQ
4672 (privileged logon) from unusual hosts
TGTs with very long validity periods

📘 Logs
SecurityEvent (4624, 4672)
Kerberos Operational logs (if collected)


SILVER TICKET
Attackers forge a service ticket (TGS) using a service account hash.

🔍 What you look for
Kerberos service logons without TGT requests
Authentication to a service (CIFS, HOST, MSSQLSvc) from unusual hosts
No corresponding 4768/4769 events
Sudden admin access to SMB or WinRM

📘 Logs
SecurityEvent (4624)
4769 (if domain controller logs are ingested)

SKELETON KEY ATTACK
A Skeleton Key attack patches LSASS on a domain controller so that any user can authenticate with a master password.

🧠 What it looks like
Skeleton Key breaks Kerberos, so attackers fall back to NTLM.

High‑signal indicators:
Sudden spike in NTLM LogonType 3 authentications
Many different accounts logging in from the same host
Successful logons for accounts that normally never authenticate on that machine
LSASS access events (Sysmon Event ID 10)
No corresponding Kerberos activity

📘 Logs to monitor
SecurityEvent (4624, 4625)
Sysmon (Event ID 10 – LSASS access)


DCSYNC ATTACK
DCSync is when an attacker impersonates a domain controller and requests password hashes from AD.

🧠 What it looks like
Non‑DC accounts performing replication operations

Event ID 4662 with specific GUIDs

Access to:

DS-Replication-Get-Changes
DS-Replication-Get-Changes-All
DS-Replication-Get-Changes-In-Filtered-Set

📘 Logs to monitor
SecurityEvent (4662, 4672)

DCSHADOW ATTACK
DCShadow registers a rogue domain controller and pushes unauthorized directory changes.

🧠 What it looks like
Object creation/deletion events (5137, 5141)

Computer account changes (4742)

Modifications to:
msDS-AllowedToActOnBehalfOfOtherIdentity
servicePrincipalName
Replication events from non‑DC hosts

📘 Logs to monitor
SecurityEvent (5137, 5141, 4742)


LATERAL MOVEMENT (WMI, WinRM, PsExec, Remote Services)
Indicators:
wmic.exe execution
Remote process creation
Powershell WMI calls (Get-WmiObject, Invoke-WmiMethod)



Useful EventIDs | Authentication & account abuse (Security log)
These are your bread-and-butter for brute force, spray, suspicious logons, lateral movement.
4624 — Successful logon (look at LogonType, source IP/workstation, auth package)
4625 — Failed logon (wrong password, disabled, locked, etc.)
4634 / 4647 — Logoff / user initiated logoff (session timelines)
4648 — Logon with explicit credentials (often used by tools / “runas” / lateral attempts)
4672 — Special privileges assigned (admin-level logon indicator)
4776 — NTLM authentication attempt (great for NTLM spray/brute force patterns)
4768 — Kerberos TGT requested (AS-REQ; great for initial auth patterns)
4769 — Kerberos service ticket requested (TGS; lateral movement + service access)
4771 — Kerberos pre-auth failed (bad password / time skew / spray hints)
4778 / 4779 — RDP session reconnect/disconnect (RDP investigations)


LogonType quick hints (4624/4625):
2 = interactive console
3 = network (SMB/LDAP/etc.)
10 = RDP
7 = unlock
(These are huge in triage.)

Privilege escalation & suspicious rights use
4673 / 4674 — Privileged service called / sensitive privilege use (can catch rare privilege abuse)
4688 — Process creation (if enabled; command line logging matters a lot)
4697 — Service installed (persistence / lateral movement)
7045 (System log, not Security) — Service installed (often more consistently collected than 4697)

Account management (Security log)
Great for detecting account takeover, persistence, and admin abuse.
4720 — User created
4722 — User enabled
4723 / 4724 — Password change attempt / password reset
4725 — User disabled
4726 — User deleted
4738 — User account changed (watch for odd attribute changes)
4740 — Account locked out (spray/brute force indicator)
4767 — User unlocked
4728 / 4729 — Added/removed from global group
4732 / 4733 — Added/removed from local group
4756 / 4757 — Added/removed from universal group


AD / Domain Controller “must-know” (Security log on DCs)
4662 — Directory Service access (very powerful for AD object access if you have SACLs set; used for AD enumeration detections)
5136 / 5137 / 5139 / 5141 — AD object modified/created/moved/deleted (needs proper auditing; very useful for “what changed?”)
4719 — Audit policy changed (defense evasion / attacker tampering)
1102 — Security log cleared (big red flag)
4616 — System time changed (Kerberos weirdness / evasion)

Lateral movement & remote execution
5140 — Network share accessed (SMB activity; use with source IP and share name)
5145 — Detailed file share access (if enabled; extremely useful but noisy)
4698 / 4699 / 4702 — Scheduled task created/deleted/updated (persistence)
4688 + 4648 combo — common in real-world remote tool usage (PSExec/WMI/etc.)


PowerShell visibility (Windows PowerShell logs)
If you can get these, they’re hunting gold:
4104 — Script block logging (best single PS event)
4103 — Module logging (noisy but useful)
400 / 403 — Engine start/stop (session boundaries)

Defender / AV (Microsoft-Windows-Windows Defender/Operational)
Highly valuable if you collect it:
1116 — Malware detected
1117 — Malware action taken
5007 — Defender config changed (can be attacker tampering)

Sysmon (if you have it)
Not “Windows Security log,” but often the best hunting telemetry:
1 — Process creation (full command line + hashes)
3 — Network connection
7 — Image loaded (DLL loads)
10 — Process access (LSASS access patterns)
11 — File create
12/13/14 — Registry create/set/value
22 — DNS query


